{"title":"SVGA-Net: Sparse Voxel-Graph Attention Network for 3D Object Detection from Point Clouds","domain":"CV","seeds":[{"problem":"3D object detectors on point clouds often fail to explicitly model relationships among local point sets and to integrate global context, limiting accuracy when using sparse LiDAR data.","method":"SVGA-Net introduces a voxel-graph network that partitions space via iterative farthest point sampling into fixed-radius spherical voxels, then constructs a local complete graph within each sphere and a global KNN graph over voxel centers. Local attention scores are softmax-normalized to aggregate features across all nodes in a sphere, while global features are obtained by a 3-layer MLP on voxel centers and refined via KNN attention (with K=3 found effective). The local and global attention factors jointly update point features through stacked point-attention layers, followed by per-voxel max pooling to produce compact features for detection."},{"problem":"Regressing accurate 3D bounding boxes from sparse point features requires effective multi-scale feature fusion, which many pipelines lack.","method":"The sparse-to-dense regression (SDR) module builds three downsampling conv blocks (b1–b3), upsamples higher-level features and concatenates them with lower-level features to align resolutions, producing dense maps F1–F3. It then fuses each original sparse map bi with its corresponding dense Fi via element-wise addition, and concatenates the fused maps followed by a 3×3 conv to obtain a final feature Fs for classification and 3D box regression. Ablations show SDR outperforms variants that remove the cross-scale concatenation (SR) or the element-wise fusion (DR)."}]}
